{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537697"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:19:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:19:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16041"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16041"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.59,0.21,0.04,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8732"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63656"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8732"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16041"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49104"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"3158"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4838"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20876"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63656"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old woman is admitted to hospital with a urinary tract infection. During the evening ward round, she reports seeing people walking past her window and shadows moving across the wall. She becomes distressed when she realises the \u0027people\u0027 are actually the branches of a tree moving in the wind. She has a history of hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her medications include amlodipine and paracetamol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly confused. Her pulse rate is 98/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Her Glasgow Coma Scale score is 14/15.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes these perceptual disturbances?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Visual agnosia","Illusions","Visual hallucinations","Delusions","Delirium tremens"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is experiencing \u003Cstrong\u003Eillusions\u003C/strong\u003E, which are misinterpretations of real sensory stimuli. In this case, she is misinterpreting the movement of tree branches as people walking past her window. Illusions commonly occur in the context of delirium, which this patient likely has given her acute infection, confusion, and vital sign changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVisual hallucinations\u003C/strong\u003E differ from illusions in that they occur without any external stimulus. They involve seeing things that are not present at all, rather than misinterpreting existing stimuli. Common examples include seeing insects or small animals that are not there.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelusions\u003C/strong\u003E are fixed, false beliefs that persist despite evidence to the contrary. They are thought disorders rather than perceptual disturbances. Unlike this patient who recognises her misperception, patients with delusions maintain their beliefs even when shown they are incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelirium tremens\u003C/strong\u003E is a severe form of alcohol withdrawal characterised by autonomic instability, confusion, and typically visual hallucinations. While this patient is confused, there is no history of alcohol use, and her symptoms are better explained by a delirium secondary to infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVisual agnosia\u003C/strong\u003E is the inability to recognise and identify objects or persons despite intact visual acuity. This is different from illusions as it involves a failure to recognise objects rather than misinterpreting them as something else.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of illusions in this case, along with confusion and an acute infection, suggests the patient has delirium which requires prompt medical assessment and treatment of the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Illusions are misperceptions of real stimuli, distinct from hallucinations which occur without external stimuli.","Illusions commonly occur in delirium and can be a sign of an acute medical condition requiring urgent assessment.","Visual illusions are more common in low-light conditions and can occur in healthy individuals."],"references":["Benjamin JS, Kaplan SJ. Sadock Comprehensive Textbook of Psychiatry."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49104"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16041"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49104"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T04:27:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T04:28:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8732"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63656"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag